GoodNet — Licensing
====================

The platform consists of the kernel and the SDK. The kernel is GPL-2.0
with a Linking Exception that releases the plugin boundary from
copyleft propagation; the SDK is MIT. Plugins are independent builds
and may carry any license — including proprietary — provided they
interface with the kernel only through the stable C ABI defined in the
SDK.


Platform Components
-------------------

  Kernel  (core/)                    GNU GPL-2.0 with Linking Exception
                                     →  core/LICENSE

  SDK     (sdk/, public headers)     MIT License
                                     →  sdk/LICENSE

  Plugins (plugins/<kind>/<name>/)   Per-plugin LICENSE; see «Plugins»
                                     below for the strategic-baseline
                                     vs periphery split.


Linking Exception (summary)
---------------------------

The full text lives in `core/LICENSE` and is part of the kernel's
license. In one sentence:

  Plugins that interface with the kernel only through `gn_plugin_descriptor`,
  the five plugin entry points, and the vtable types declared in public
  `sdk/` headers are not derivative works of the kernel — they may be
  licensed under any terms (MIT, BSD, Apache 2.0, proprietary, …) and
  linked statically or dynamically.

What the exception does NOT cover:

  - Modifications to the kernel itself (sources under `core/` and the
    mandatory mesh-framing under `plugins/protocols/gnet/`). A modified
    kernel must be redistributed under GPL-2.0.
  - Plugins that reach past the SDK and reference internal kernel
    symbols or `core/` headers directly. Such code is a derivative
    work of the kernel and inherits GPL-2.0.

The rationale: the kernel itself stays free in the strong sense, while
the plugin layer is open to any business model — open-source ecosystem,
commercial dual-license, embedded proprietary differentiation. This is
the OpenJDK GPL-with-Classpath-Exception model, written explicitly so
the legal status that Linux has lived with as a "gray area" for thirty
years is unambiguous here.


Plugins
-------

Plugins are independent builds. Each carries its own LICENSE file in
its directory. The Linking Exception above means any license is
permitted for plugins that interface with the kernel only through the
stable C ABI in the SDK.

In-tree licensing for the bundled plugins shipped in this repository:

  Strategic baseline — community-locked under GPL-2.0 with the same
  Linking Exception as the kernel. The kernel's value as an
  anti-enclosure platform depends on these layers staying free in
  the strong sense; a fork must publish its modifications.

    - plugins/protocols/gnet      .. GPL-2.0 + Linking Exception
                                     (mandatory mesh framing)
    - plugins/links/tcp           .. GPL-2.0 + Linking Exception
    - plugins/links/udp           .. GPL-2.0 + Linking Exception
    - plugins/links/ws            .. GPL-2.0 + Linking Exception
                                     (web access bet — strategic)
    - plugins/security/noise      .. GPL-2.0 + Linking Exception
    - plugins/handlers/heartbeat  .. GPL-2.0 + Linking Exception
                                     (canonical reference handler)

  Periphery — permissive. Templates, debug providers, host-OS-tied
  transports without strategic weight.

    - plugins/security/null       .. MIT License
                                     (loopback / IntraNode-only debug)
    - plugins/protocols/raw       .. MIT License
                                     (template; opaque-payload layer)
    - plugins/links/ipc           .. MIT License
                                     (local AF_UNIX socket)

  OpenSSL-tied — Apache-2.0 to align with OpenSSL 3.x and avoid the
  GPL-2 ↔ Apache-2.0 incompatibility on the link.

    - plugins/links/tls           .. Apache-2.0 License

Out-of-tree plugins choose freely; the Linking Exception applies
regardless of the plugin's license, so a proprietary plugin loaded
through the SDK does not contaminate the kernel binary.

License compatibility detail: Apache-2.0 is incompatible with
GPL-2.0 on a static-link boundary because of Apache's patent-
retaliation clause. The Linking Exception releases the SDK boundary
from that restriction for plugin loading; the OpenSSL-tied TLS
plugin keeps Apache-2.0 internally so it can continue linking
OpenSSL without an additional exception clause. See
`docs/LICENSES.md` for the full compatibility matrix and the
upstream-dependency licence audit.


